	   <tr><td colspan=2>But according to a post down below someone said that the class wouldnt be good for dungeon hunting. But if I remember correctly, I think that beastlords get the ability to tell there pets not to attack, even if they are attacked, or their master is attacked. Might be an AA or might just be a new /pet command, either one, but I do remember seeing somewhere you can have it so your pet WON'T&nbsp;&nbsp;attack no matter what. And as for dungeons, I find mage pets in sebilis to be quite handy. Most mages can keep there pet under control, and they got the pets now so they dont wander as much as they used to. So I could say it would still be pretty safe for beasties to kill in dungeons. <br><br>As for beasts effectiveness in raids, I would say they would be nice assistant slowers for the shamans or chanters. Although not as good shamans or chanters by a long shot, if your shaman or chanter are low on mana, they would more than make up for a good slower on lesser mobs along the way. Even though they are great damage dealers. They are no rogues, or wizards, but they do their fair share of help in killing. With the ability to hold there own with there pets and all, they are less of a burden to Clerics or other healers while grouping as other melee classes are. Because unlike monks or rangers, they can med through battles and let their pets do nice damage, and save up to heal themselves in a tight situation. If they have enough life, they can help there pets out, and match or beat the damage done by the groups monk or low lvl rogue (i say low lvl rogue cause a high lvl rogue, especially epic rogue, is pretty much untouchable in damage dealing). Mages dont have that healing ability so a healer is necissary. Necros can siphon life, but that always comes at the risk of agro. Overall, in my mind they would be a welcome addition to any group or raiding force. <br>&nbsp;<br>If winners never quit, and quitters never win... Who the hell came up with the phrase quit while your ahead?</td></tr>
